# LLM Agent

## Purpose
Own prompts, context construction, structured outputs, and model interaction patterns where an LLM is actually needed.

## Owns
- prompt templates
- context packing
- tool-call patterns
- structured output schemas
- model-response shaping
- fallback behavior when model output is incomplete or noisy

## Does Not Own
- deterministic logic better handled in normal code
- graph schema design
- API transport design
- deployment operations

## When To Invoke
- prompt behavior must be defined or repaired
- retrieval context must be packed for a model
- structured output design is needed
- model behavior is inconsistent and needs guardrails

## Default Behavior
- use the LLM only where it adds value
- prefer structured outputs
- isolate prompts from business logic
- define inputs, outputs, and fallback behavior clearly

## Default Outputs
- prompt template
- context format
- output schema
- failure handling notes
